\begin_layout Title
Intragenomic conflict over mating preferences and ornament investment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What is happening with madumnal, maternal etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First of all, everything is a tradeoff between fecundity (benefits of ornamentat
ion) vs adult survival (costs of ornamentation).
 We can write most sexual selection problems such as investment in ornamentation
 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as a tradeoff problem, where the following should apply
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu^{\prime}(t)/\mu(t) & =f^{\prime}(t)/f(t).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

I.e., the marginal mortality costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{\prime}(t)/\mu(t)$
\end_inset

 should be equal to the marginal fecundity gains 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{\prime}(t)/f(t)$
\end_inset

.
 Here, primes (
\begin_inset Formula $^{\prime}$
\end_inset

) note derivatives, reflecting the cost or benefit of a slightly higher
 investment in ornamentation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, in a viscous population like the one we are studying, it is slightly
 different
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\overbrace{\left(r_{\mathrm{self}}-r_{\mathrm{competing\ adults}}\right)}^{A}\frac{\mu^{\prime}\left(t\right)}{\mu\left(t\right)} & =\overbrace{\left(r_{\text{own offspring}}-r_{\text{competing offspring}}\right)}^{B}\frac{f^{\prime}\left(t\right)}{f\left(t\right)}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the left-hand side (lhs) reflects the marginal mortality cost of ornamenta
tion and the right-hand side (rhs) reflects the marginal fecundity benefit
 of ornamentation in terms of matings.
 The mortality cost on the lhs is discounted by term 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, which considers the fact that if competing adults are closely related
 to the focal adult (hence 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is small), then there is only a limited cost of dying, as it is likely
 that the focal adult will be replaced by a relative.
 Similarly, also the fecundity benefit on the rhs is discounted by the fact
 that siring a lot of offspring will displace those offspring from relatives.
 Hence, if those competing offspring are closely related to the focal's
 own offspring (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is small), then it takes a lot of investment in ornamentation to make any
 gains relative to a well mixed population.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The different relatedness coefficients are weighed differently dependent
 on the type of genetic control and the degree of dispersal.
\end_layout

